# Typed Custom Page Sections Redesign

## Context

Custom pages currently serialize an array of sections into `pages.content`, and
each section serializes `config` a second time as a JSON string. The frontend
duplicates section metadata and parses configs independently inside block
components, while the backend registry has complete validation only for
interactive and integration sections. Shared layout, spacing, animation, and
background behavior is read by `BlockRenderer`, but every block still embeds its
own toolbar and config mutations.

The database also contains legacy global `page_sections` and `page_items` tables
used by dormant `internal/config` repository methods. They are not the storage
model for custom pages and must not be repurposed without an explicit data audit.

This plan intentionally supersedes only the future section-storage and typing
parts of `.todo/ui_component_refactor_plan`; component rendering/bind-point work
remains there. The implemented JSON-backed interactive behavior in
`.specs/custom_page_interactive_sections_spec` remains authoritative until a
verified migration changes it.

## Production Baseline (2026-07-17)

The sanitized `cueballcraft` and `thewriterco` inventory in local `output.txt`
establishes the migration baseline. The raw export contains production page
content and must not be committed; derive minimal anonymized compatibility
fixtures from these shapes.

- The two tenants contain 16 pages and 59 section instances. `cueballcraft` has
  4 pages/14 sections and no saved custom sections; `thewriterco` has 12
  pages/45 sections and 7 saved custom sections.
- Both legacy global `page_sections` and `page_items` tables are empty in both
  tenants. A migration must still recheck every tenant and fail closed if rows
  appear before those tables are renamed or retired.
- Production section config is heterogeneous: 53 sections store `config` as a
  JSON-encoded string and 6 seeded sections store it as a JSON object. Adapters
  must accept both forms and emit one canonical object without double encoding.
- The seeded `get-started` page exists in both tenants with string section/item
  IDs (`gs-*`), object configs, and legacy section type `features`. Other pages
  use a mix of small imported integers and timestamp-sized integers.
- Section IDs are page-scoped in practice, not globally unique. Duplicated pages
  reuse source section IDs, including the `payroll`/`payroll-copy` pair. New
  storage needs a server-owned primary key plus a `(page_id, legacy_key)` mapping;
  a direct cast into a globally unique numeric ID is invalid.
- Nine existing pages use an empty visibility string, which current read logic
  effectively treats as non-private. Migration must preserve access behavior and
  normalize it explicitly to `public` only through a verified compatibility rule.
  One page is intentionally empty and must remain valid.
- Production uses 12 page section types, including unsupported legacy
  `features`, and includes rich-text HTML with inline styles, negative spacing,
  uploaded media/iframes, gallery albums/widths, multi-video heroes, profile
  data, code/markdown, social links, interactive sections, and datasource-backed
  custom sections.
- Saved `custom_sections` are a distinct datasource-preset domain. Their live
  `section_type` values are `table`, `cards`, and `component`; component presets
  contain string component-group IDs, bind maps, event-hook arrays, max widths,
  and constrained custom CSS. A page `custom_section` currently references saved
  preset ID 5. These values must not be validated as page `SectionType`s or
  conflated with page section instances during renaming.

## Goal

- Give every page block one shared, typed section shell and a discriminated,
  versioned section-specific config.
- Make the backend registry the canonical runtime authority for type metadata,
  defaults, schema versions, capabilities, validation, and migration.
- Normalize page-owned section identity, order, shared presentation, revisions,
  and reusable items into relational tables without creating a table per block.
- Move data with an independent security/concurrency lifecycle, especially
  interactive responses, out of presentation config.
- Preserve live propagation as a mandatory correctness property: every page,
  palette, section, item, preset, and interactive mutation must converge across
  active clients through backend-authoritative, revision-guarded REST writes and
  content-free WebSocket invalidations.
- Give every section the same palette-aware background and typography controls,
  bounded content scaling, and accessible collapse behavior through the shared
  shell contract.
- Preserve every current section type, visual behavior, editor operation,
  permission boundary, copy/duplicate rule, and realtime behavior through an
  expand/migrate/contract rollout with a rollback path.

## Non-Goals

- Rewriting all block renderers at once or replacing `BlockRenderer` with a
  second rendering system.
- Creating one database table per section type or an EAV property table.
- Making registry definitions or validation schemas freely mutable production
  data.
- Combining this work with AI page generation, arbitrary component execution,
  or a broad design-system rewrite.
- Removing the legacy `pages.content` projection before parity and rollback
  requirements have been met.

## Target Contract

1. **Canonical schemas and generated types**
   - Define one versioned schema per supported section type plus shared shell and
     item schemas. Generate or drift-check TypeScript discriminated unions and Go
     DTO/validation bindings from the same canonical contracts.
   - Registry entries expose `type`, label/group/description, current
     `config_version`, defaults, capabilities, config schema, item schema, and
     supported migrations.
   - Frontend code uses `PageSection<T>` / `SectionConfigByType[T]`; no public
     section boundary exposes `section_type: string`, `config: string`, `any`, or
     `as never` casts.
   - Compatibility decoding accepts object configs and legacy JSON-encoded
     strings, maps `features` to canonical `feature_grid`, and preserves unknown
     fields in a quarantined round-trip representation until a type migration
     explicitly owns them.

2. **One section shell**
   - `SectionFrame` owns the toolbar, layout/container width, spacing,
     background, animation, edit/move/copy/cut/delete states, suspense,
     unknown/error state, and accessibility hooks. Renderers retain semantic
     heading/subheading placement and inline content editing where their DOM
     structures differ; they do not recreate shared shell controls.
   - Every section toolbar exposes the same background, ordinary text, `h1`,
     `h2`, and `h3` color controls. Each override can explicitly inherit, refer
     to a page palette token, or use a validated section-local color without
     changing the shared palette.
   - The shared appearance editor is portaled outside section/toolbar overflow,
     follows its trigger during scroll and resize, flips above or below according
     to available space, and remains reachable within the viewport. Literal
     fields use the shared native color picker for visual and precise entry.
   - `SectionFrame` applies a schema-bounded `content_scale` only to an inner
     content wrapper. Scaling must use responsive sizing variables/layout rather
     than transforming the outer section box; it may increase section height but
     must not create horizontal page overflow, clipped controls, or unreachable
     content.
   - The shell supports `collapsible` and an authored `default_collapsed` state
     with an accessible `aria-expanded` trigger. Editors may persist these shell
     settings. A viewer without edit permission keeps expand/collapse state only
     in current-page memory keyed by page, section, and revision: React rerenders
     retain it, while reload, navigation, or an authoritative section revision
     resets it to the authored default and never writes to the backend.
   - A typed registry maps each section type to its lazy renderer, editor,
     defaults, capabilities, and clipboard sanitizer. Block renderers receive
     typed section-specific config and content callbacks only.
   - Shared presentation is separated from section config so block-specific
     updates cannot accidentally erase shell fields.

3. **Unified custom-page palette and safe color resolution**
   - A page owns a versioned palette of stable, validated token keys and CSS color
     values. The renderer exposes only namespaced generated CSS variables; user
     input cannot choose arbitrary CSS variable names, properties, or declarations.
   - Shared section color fields store either a palette-token reference or a
     validated literal value with explicit inherit/clear semantics. Palette token
     deletion must be rejected while referenced or require an explicit atomic
     replacement/fallback operation.
   - Palette and per-section color editors provide previews, reset/inherit
     controls, keyboard labels, and contrast warnings for background/text pairs.
     Backend validation remains authoritative and blocks unsafe or malformed CSS.
   - Define and test color precedence for rich-text inline styles and constrained
     custom-section CSS. A section-level typography override must have explicit
     documented semantics; migration may not strip or silently override existing
     inline author colors.
   - Palette edits carry a page-theme revision and propagate live to every open
     instance of that page without broadcasting private page content.

4. **Hybrid relational persistence**
   - Add page-owned section tables under unambiguous names until the legacy
     `page_sections`/`page_items` data is audited. The section row contains
     `page_id`, server-owned ID, order key, section type, heading/subheading,
     typed shared presentation columns (including color references/literals,
     bounded content scale, and collapse settings), `config JSONB`,
     `config_version`, revision, audit columns, and timestamps.
   - Give each normalized section/item a new server-owned primary key and retain
     the original numeric-or-string identity as a page/section-scoped legacy key
     for compatibility projection, idempotent backfill, interactive-route
     mapping, and rollback. Never assume copied legacy IDs are globally unique.
   - Add page palette/theme tables with stable token keys, validated color values,
     deterministic order, page ownership, audit metadata, and revisions. Palette
     references must retain referential integrity across section mutations.
   - Store reusable list/card/gallery entries as page-section items with stable
     server IDs, order, common content/media/link columns, versioned item config,
     and a section foreign key.
   - Keep section-specific config in validated JSONB. Promote only fields that
     need constraints, joins, authorization, independent writes, or operational
     queries; do not proliferate per-type tables.
   - Store interactive records in response tables with section/user/idempotency
     constraints and JSONB answers. Definitions remain section config; raw
     records never enter page render, clipboard, duplicate, cache, or WebSocket
     projections.
   - Model reusable saved designs as versioned section presets containing a
     section type, shell defaults, config, and item templates. Insertion creates
     a page-owned snapshot by default so later preset edits do not silently alter
     published pages.

5. **Fine-grained API, live propagation, and concurrency**
   - Add typed palette, section CRUD, reorder, item, preset, and interactive
     endpoints while keeping the current page response adapter during migration.
   - Use server-generated IDs, per-section revisions/optimistic concurrency, and
     transactional ordering. Return conflict payloads suitable for builder merge
     UI instead of relying on whole-document last-writer-wins saves.
   - Live propagation is non-negotiable for both legacy and normalized modes:
     `REST mutation -> backend policy/validation -> transaction with expected
     revision -> cache/SEO invalidation -> content-free WebSocket invalidation ->
     authorized REST refetch -> merge by stable ID and revision`.
   - Realtime payloads include page identity, affected palette/section/item IDs,
     and authoritative revisions but never raw page documents, response records,
     answers, private config, or idempotency keys. Concurrent edits to different
     sections converge independently; same-revision conflicts fail explicitly
     instead of silently overwriting either editor.
   - WebSocket reconnect replays the page subscription and refetches revisions so
     a disconnected editor cannot miss palette or section changes.

## Steps

1. **Freeze the existing behavior contract**
   - Inventory all 19 section types, every shell/config/item field and default,
     legacy aliases (`wide`, `video_url`, unified padding), edit controls, empty
     states, clipboard/duplicate behavior, datasource bindings, and interactive
     privacy rules.
   - Export representative production-safe fixtures and add golden round-trip
     render/save/copy/duplicate tests before changing storage.
   - Collect a sanitized cross-client inventory from `cueballcraft` and
     `thewriterco`: page/section/item counts, section-type counts, config key/type
     histograms, schema/table metadata, ID/order anomalies, legacy aliases, and
     invalid payload counts. Do not dump interactive `records`/answers,
     respondent data, idempotency keys, datasource environment values, secrets,
     or unrelated user content.
   - Treat the 2026-07-17 inventory as the initial baseline and repeat the same
     sanitized count/shape checks immediately before backfill and cutover so
     newly created pages/config variants cannot be missed.
   - Inventory every existing page WebSocket producer/consumer, subscription,
     cache/SEO invalidation, edit guard, reconnect path, and merge behavior as a
     baseline live-propagation contract.
   - Audit whether legacy `page_sections`/`page_items` contain required data;
     the two current tenants are empty, but the migration must assert emptiness
     transactionally and stop for manual review if any tenant has gained rows
     before renaming or retiring them.

2. **Establish the schema package and registry authority**
   - Use JSON Schema 2020-12 as the checked-in canonical source. The embedded v1
     page-theme, shared-shell, normalized item/preset, and all 19 per-type config
     contracts are public through `GET /config/section-contracts`. They define
     explicit defaults, bounds, formats, required fields, and unknown-key policy.
     The shell schema includes typed color sources, background/text/heading
     overrides, bounded content scale, `collapsible`, and `default_collapsed`.
   - Model legacy string/object config storage, `gs-*` identities, `features`,
     empty visibility, optional embedded timestamps, negative spacing, and item
     configs at the compatibility boundary. The checked-in fixtures, adapter
     input types, and round-trip tests own these permissive legacy shapes; the
     normalized JSON Schemas remain strict.
   - `s_registry.Definition` derives version/default/capability/item metadata from
     the canonical contracts. `ValidateContractValue` resolves only embedded
     references and validates every normalized contract/default; safe CSS colors
     receive explicit validation because JSON Schema format annotations are not
     assertions. Typed mutation services must call it only after the legacy
     compatibility adapter separates shared shell and runtime records.
   - Add generation/drift checks so frontend types, backend DTOs, defaults, and
     registry API fixtures cannot diverge. The frontend section-type/config map,
     versions, defaults, and capabilities plus normalized Go discriminators/config
     DTOs are generated from backend contracts. The Go decode factory performs
     bounded duplicate-key-safe JSON parsing, schema validation, and typed decode;
     the frontend now exposes generated shared-shell/config types through the
     generic normalized `PageSection<T>` boundary. This completes the schema and
     typed-registry phase; typed mutation-service wiring belongs to Phase 5 after
     normalized persistence exists.

3. **Refactor the frontend shell without changing persistence**
   - The compatibility adapter now parses object/string config, resolves legacy
     type and config aliases, separates shell/config/runtime fields, retains
     page-scoped numeric-or-string keys, quarantines unknown input, and projects
     normalized sections back to the current `pages.content` envelope. Existing
     renderers keep the default `LegacyPageSection` save envelope during the
     compatibility window while `SectionFrame` consumes generated
     `SharedSectionShell` values and projects edits back through the adapter.
   - One `SectionFrame` toolbar now covers every registered and unsupported
     section. All 15 block-local shared toolbars are removed; six renderer
     families portal only their type-specific actions into the frame toolbar.
   - An exhaustive typed renderer registry owns lazy renderers, generated
     versions/defaults/capabilities, and clipboard sanitizers without `as never`
     dispatch casts. The visible unsupported/error fallback remains framed.
   - The shared appearance editor owns safe literal/palette/inherit colors,
     contrast warnings, container width, bounded overflow-safe content scaling,
     and permission-aware accessible collapse state. Palette values resolve only
     through declared namespaced variables.
   - Renderer families retain their existing semantic heading/subheading
     placement and inline editing because their DOM structures differ. Shared
     presentation and actions live exclusively in the frame, preserving the
     compatibility snapshots while completing Phase 3.

4. **Add normalized storage in shadow mode**
   - Migration 030 and the fresh schema now define page themes/tokens, section
     instances, palette references, items, presets, responses, quarantine, and
     shadow-run telemetry with foreign keys, constraints, indexes, revisions,
     stable server IDs, and audit ownership columns.
   - Page creates and builder updates transactionally maintain normalized shadow
     rows while `pages.content` remains authoritative. Projectors preserve
     page-scoped numeric/string legacy keys, source order, display order,
     object/string config encoding, media, rich HTML, items, unknown fields, and
     alias/default audit facts.
   - Invalid/unsupported inputs are quarantined without logging values. Runtime
     interactive records and summaries are excluded from section config and are
     not copied into the response table before the Phase 6 sensitive migration.
   - The bounded `page-section-shadow-backfill` command resumes by page ID and
     records hashes, counts, repair/quarantine counts, mismatch codes, and run
     counters. Canonical definition projection parity is covered by sanitized
     production fixtures and real PostgreSQL tests; Phase 4 is complete.

5. **Move to typed APIs behind feature flags**
   - Add section-scoped mutations and update the builder to use them while the
     service transactionally maintains the legacy document projection for old
     clients and rollback.
   - Preserve page visibility, owner/editor/admin policies, cache invalidation,
     SEO invalidation, realtime refresh, response management, and allocation
     behavior.
   - Add explicit revision conflicts and verify concurrent edits to different
     sections no longer overwrite one another.
   - Route palette/color/scale/collapse writes through the same service policy,
     transaction, revision, invalidation, WebSocket, and reconciliation path as
     every other section mutation; feature flags must not create a propagation
     bypass in either storage mode.

6. **Migrate sensitive and reusable domains**
   - Move interactive records last through a verified, resumable migration with
     count/idempotency/user/answer parity and negative-disclosure tests.
   - Introduce presets as a compatibility evolution of current reusable
     `custom_sections`; retain route/type aliases until references are migrated
     and terminology no longer collides with page section instances.

7. **Cut over and contract**
   - Require a sustained zero-diff shadow-read window, successful rollback drill,
     complete fixture migration, and full authorization/concurrency test matrix.
   - Switch reads to normalized storage, keep the legacy projection for one
     release window, then remove document writes only after telemetry confirms no
     old clients or jobs depend on them.
   - Update `.specs/custom_page_interactive_sections_spec`, frontend/backend
     specs, migration docs, and overlapping todos only when implementation truth
     changes; then retire superseded code and plans.
   - Phase closure delivers the guarded cutover and non-destructive retirement
     preflight. Production document-write/table retirement remains forbidden until
     the real release-window telemetry and external dependency attestation pass;
     do not simulate that evidence in development or migration SQL.

## Verification

- Schema drift: generated artifacts are clean and all 19 types have defaults,
  current version, backend validation, typed frontend registration, and fixtures.
- Migration: old -> new -> old canonical round trips produce zero semantic diff;
  row counts, IDs, order, media, item config, and interactive record ownership
  match; reruns are idempotent.
- Production compatibility fixtures cover string and object configs, `gs-*`
  section/item IDs, copied page-scoped ID collisions, legacy `features`, empty
  visibility, empty pages, negative spacing, inline rich-text styles, gallery
  albums, multi-video heroes, and `table`/`cards`/`component` datasource presets.
- Backend: full Go suite plus DB-backed migration, concurrent section edit,
  reorder, palette referential-integrity, color-validation, scale-bound,
  collapse-permission, duplicate, preset snapshot, response idempotency, and
  rollback tests.
- Frontend: lint/build plus exhaustive registry, parser/migrator, shell capability,
  renderer parity, editor, clipboard, unknown type, and conflict-state tests.
- Shared presentation: every section type exposes background/text/`h1`/`h2`/`h3`
  controls; palette references and literals resolve identically after reload;
  invalid colors are rejected; contrast warnings remain usable; bounded scaling
  causes no horizontal overflow at supported breakpoints; the appearance editor
  remains viewport-bounded above and below its anchor at supported breakpoints.
- Collapse behavior: authored defaults persist and propagate only for authorized
  editors; unauthorized viewer toggles survive ordinary rerenders but make no
  mutation and reset on reload, navigation, or authoritative section revision.
- Live propagation: two-browser and reconnect tests cover page metadata, palette,
  all shared shell fields, section config, items, reorder, copy/delete, presets,
  and interactive mutations. Different-section edits converge, same-section
  stale revisions return a conflict, and no live path broadcasts private content.
- Security: guest/participant/other participant/editor/owner/admin matrix proves
  raw responses and privileged config never leak through page reads, caches,
  presets, duplicates, exports, logs, or WebSocket messages.
- Operations: shadow-read mismatch metrics, migration progress/quarantine counts,
  feature flags, and rollback runbook are exercised before cutover.

